{"parse":{"title":"Periodic sentence","pageid":2664203,"revid":780750732,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>A <b>periodic sentence </b> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Stylistic_device\" title=\"Stylistic device\">stylistic device</a> employed at the sentence level, described as one that is not complete grammatically or semantically before the final clause or phrase.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Characteristics\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Characteristics</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Decline\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Decline</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Rhetorical_and_literary_usage\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Rhetorical and literary usage</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Characteristics\">Characteristics</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Periodic_sentence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Characteristics\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The periodic sentence emphasizes its main idea by placing it at the end, following all the <a href=\"/wiki/Subordinate_clauses\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Subordinate clauses\">subordinate clauses</a> and other <a href=\"/wiki/Grammatical_modifier\" title=\"Grammatical modifier\">modifiers</a> that support the principal idea.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Baldwin1909_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Baldwin1909-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The sentence unfolds gradually, so that the thought contained in the <a href=\"/wiki/Subject_(grammar)\" title=\"Subject (grammar)\">subject</a>/<a href=\"/wiki/Verb\" title=\"Verb\">verb</a> group only emerges at the sentence's conclusion.<sup id=\"cite_ref-harmon_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-harmon-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> Obviously artificial, it is used mostly in what in <a href=\"/wiki/Eloquence\" title=\"Eloquence\">oratory</a> is called the grand style.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>It is the opposite of the <a href=\"/wiki/Loose_sentence\" title=\"Loose sentence\">loose sentence</a>, also continuous or running style, where the subject and verb are introduced at the beginning of the sentence.<sup id=\"cite_ref-harmon_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-harmon-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> Periodic sentences often rely on <a href=\"/wiki/Hypotaxis\" title=\"Hypotaxis\">hypotaxis</a>, whereas running sentences are typified by <a href=\"/wiki/Parataxis\" title=\"Parataxis\">parataxis</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-routledge_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-routledge-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/Cicero\" title=\"Cicero\">Cicero</a> is generally considered to be the master of the periodic sentence.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Decline\">Decline</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Periodic_sentence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Decline\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In English literature, the decline of the periodic sentence's popularity goes hand in hand with the development toward a less formal style, which some authors date to the beginning of the Romantic period, specifically the 1798 publication of the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Lyrical_Ballads\" title=\"Lyrical Ballads\">Lyrical Ballads</a></i>, and the prevalence in twentieth-century literature of spoken language over written language.<sup id=\"cite_ref-routledge_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-routledge-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> In American literature, scholars note the explicit rejection by <a href=\"/wiki/Henry_David_Thoreau\" title=\"Henry David Thoreau\">Henry David Thoreau</a> of the formal style of his time, of which the periodic sentence was characteristic; in his journal, Thoreau criticized those sentences as the \"weak and flowing periods of the politician and scholar.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Rhetorical_and_literary_usage\">Rhetorical and literary usage</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Periodic_sentence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Rhetorical and literary usage\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>According to <a href=\"/wiki/William_Harmon\" title=\"William Harmon\">William Harmon</a>, the periodic sentence is used \"to arouse interest and curiosity, to hold an idea in suspense before its final revelation.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-harmon_3-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-harmon-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> In the words of <a href=\"/wiki/William_Minto\" title=\"William Minto\">William Minto</a>, \"the effect...is to keep the mind in a state of uniform or increasing tension until the <i>d\u00e9nouement</i>.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>In his <i>Handbook to Literature</i>, Harmon offers an early example in American literature found in <a href=\"/wiki/Henry_Wadsworth_Longfellow\" title=\"Henry Wadsworth Longfellow\">Longfellow</a>\u2019s \"Snowflakes\":<sup id=\"cite_ref-harmon_3-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-harmon-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<dl><dd>Out of the bosom of the Air,</dd>\n<dd>Out of the cloud-folds of her garment shaken,</dd>\n<dd>Over the woodlands brown and bare,</dd>\n<dd>Over the harvest-fields forsaken,</dd>\n<dd>Silent and soft, and slow,</dd>\n<dd>Descends the snow.</dd></dl>\n<p>Starting with a succession of parallel adverbial phrases (\"Out of the bosom,\" \"Out of the cloud-folds,\" \"Over the woodlands,\" \"Over the harvest-fields\"), each followed by parallel modification (\"of the air,\" \"of her garment shaken,\" \"brown and bare,\" \"forsaken\"), the sentence is left grammatically incomplete until the <a href=\"/wiki/Subject_(grammar)\" title=\"Subject (grammar)\">subject</a>/<a href=\"/wiki/Verb\" title=\"Verb\">verb</a> group \"Descends the snow\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-harmon_3-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-harmon-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> Other American examples cited include the opening lines of <a href=\"/wiki/William_Cullen_Bryant\" title=\"William Cullen Bryant\">William Cullen Bryant</a>'s \"<a href=\"/wiki/A_Forest_Hymn\" title=\"A Forest Hymn\">A Forest Hymn</a>\" and lines 9-16 of his \"<a href=\"/wiki/Thanatopsis\" title=\"Thanatopsis\">Thanatopsis</a>\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> A particularly long example is the opening stanza (lines 1-22) of <a href=\"/wiki/Walt_Whitman\" title=\"Walt Whitman\">Walt Whitman</a>'s \"<a href=\"/wiki/Out_of_the_Cradle_Endlessly_Rocking\" title=\"Out of the Cradle Endlessly Rocking\">Out of the Cradle Endlessly Rocking</a>.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>A \"now-famous periodic sentence\" occurs in <a href=\"/wiki/Nikolai_Gogol\" title=\"Nikolai Gogol\">Nikolai Gogol</a>'s short story \"<a href=\"/wiki/The_Overcoat\" title=\"The Overcoat\">The Overcoat</a>\":<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<dl><dd>Even at those hours when the gray Petersburg sky is completely overcast and the whole population of clerks have dined and eaten their fill, each as best he can, according to the salary he receives and his personal tastes; when they are all resting after the scratching of pens and bustle of the office, their own necessary work and other people's, and all the tasks that an overzealous man voluntarily sets himself even beyond what is necessary; when the clerks are hastening to devote what is left of their time to pleasure; some more enterprising are flying to the theater, others to the street to spend their leisure staring at women's hats, some to spend the evening paying compliments to some attractive girl, the star of a little official circle, while some\u2014and this is the most frequent of all\u2014go simply to a fellow clerk's apartment on the third or fourth story, two little rooms with a hall or a kitchen, with some pretensions to style, with a lamp or some such article that has cost many sacrifices of dinners and excursions\u2014at the time when all the clerks are scattered about the apartments of their friends, playing a stormy game of whist, sipping tea out of glasses, eating cheap biscuits, sucking in smoke from long pipes, telling, as the cards are dealt, some scandal that has floated down from higher circles, a pleasure which the Russian do never by any possibility deny himself, or, when there is nothing better to talk about, repeating the everlasting anecdote of the commanding officer who was told that the tail had been cut off the horse on the Falconet monument\u2014in short, even when everyone, was eagerly seeking entertainment, Akaky Akakievich did not indulge in any amusement.<sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup></dd></dl>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Periodic_sentence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Euphuism\" title=\"Euphuism\">Euphuism</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Periodic_sentence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\"><a href=\"/wiki/Cicero\" title=\"Cicero\">Cicero, Marcus Tullius</a> (1999).  Stephen Ciraolo, ed. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=huar3SdjthAC&amp;pg=PA3\"><i>Pro Caelio</i></a> (2 ed.). Bolchazy-Carducci Publishers. p.&#160;3. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-86516-461-1\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-86516-461-1\">978-0-86516-461-1</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Pro+Caelio&amp;rft.pages=3&amp;rft.edition=2&amp;rft.pub=Bolchazy-Carducci+Publishers&amp;rft.date=1999&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-86516-461-1&amp;rft.aulast=Cicero&amp;rft.aufirst=Marcus+Tullius&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3Dhuar3SdjthAC%26pg%3DPA3&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APeriodic+sentence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Baldwin1909-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Baldwin1909_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Baldwin, Charles Sears (1909). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=P3BLAAAAMAAJ&amp;pg=PA122\"><i>Composition, Oral and Written</i></a>. Longmans, Green and Co. p.&#160;122<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">7 July</span> 2011</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Composition%2C+Oral+and+Written&amp;rft.pages=122&amp;rft.pub=Longmans%2C+Green+and+Co.&amp;rft.date=1909&amp;rft.aulast=Baldwin&amp;rft.aufirst=Charles+Sears&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DP3BLAAAAMAAJ%26pg%3DPA122&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APeriodic+sentence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span> <img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/62/PD-icon.svg/15px-PD-icon.svg.png\" width=\"15\" height=\"15\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/62/PD-icon.svg/23px-PD-icon.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/62/PD-icon.svg/30px-PD-icon.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"196\" data-file-height=\"196\" /> <i>This article incorporates text from this source, which is in the <a href=\"/wiki/Public_domain\" title=\"Public domain\">public domain</a>.</i></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-harmon-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-harmon_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-harmon_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-harmon_3-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-harmon_3-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-harmon_3-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Harmon, William (2006). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=nyrzAAAAMAAJ&amp;q=%22periodic+sentence%22+snowflakes&amp;dq=%22periodic+sentence%22+snowflakes\"><i>A handbook to literature</i></a> (10 ed.). Pearson/Prentice Hall. p.&#160;386. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-13-134442-6\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-13-134442-6\">978-0-13-134442-6</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=A+handbook+to+literature&amp;rft.pages=386&amp;rft.edition=10&amp;rft.pub=Pearson%2FPrentice+Hall&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-13-134442-6&amp;rft.aulast=Harmon&amp;rft.aufirst=William&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DnyrzAAAAMAAJ%26q%3D%2522periodic%2Bsentence%2522%2Bsnowflakes%26dq%3D%2522periodic%2Bsentence%2522%2Bsnowflakes&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APeriodic+sentence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\"><a href=\"/wiki/Cicero\" title=\"Cicero\">Cicero, Marcus Tullius</a> (1993).  Harold C. Gotoff, ed. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=aAokWH3m1aEC&amp;pg=PA279\"><i>Cicero's Caesarian speeches: a stylistic commentary</i></a>. UNC Press. p.&#160;279. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-8078-4407-6\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-8078-4407-6\">978-0-8078-4407-6</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Cicero%27s+Caesarian+speeches%3A+a+stylistic+commentary&amp;rft.pages=279&amp;rft.pub=UNC+Press&amp;rft.date=1993&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-8078-4407-6&amp;rft.aulast=Cicero&amp;rft.aufirst=Marcus+Tullius&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DaAokWH3m1aEC%26pg%3DPA279&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APeriodic+sentence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-routledge-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-routledge_5-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-routledge_5-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Carter, Ronald; McRae, John (2001). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=rRR7nR8qOAMC&amp;pg=PA475\"><i>The Routledge history of literature in English: Britain and Ireland</i></a>. Routledge. p.&#160;475. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-415-24317-9\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-415-24317-9\">978-0-415-24317-9</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Routledge+history+of+literature+in+English%3A+Britain+and+Ireland&amp;rft.pages=475&amp;rft.pub=Routledge&amp;rft.date=2001&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-415-24317-9&amp;rft.aulast=Carter&amp;rft.aufirst=Ronald&amp;rft.au=McRae%2C+John&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DrRR7nR8qOAMC%26pg%3DPA475&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2